Note:
Runa Standard Library: Random Sampling Module

Advanced sampling algorithms and statistical utilities surpassing
NumPy, R, MATLAB, and specialized statistical packages.

Features:
- Reservoir sampling for streaming data
- Weighted and stratified sampling
- Latin hypercube sampling
- Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) methods
- Importance and rejection sampling
- Bootstrap and jackknife resampling
- Permutation and combination generation
- Alias method for efficient discrete sampling
:End Note

Import "../../collections" as Collections
Import "math/core" as Math
Import "random/generator" as Generator
Import "random/distributions" as Distributions

Note: Sampling types
Type SamplingMethod is:
    | Simple
    | Systematic
    | Stratified
    | Cluster
    | Multistage
    | Weighted
    | ReservoirSampling

Type called "Sampler":
    method as SamplingMethod
    generator as Generator.RandomGenerator
    population_size as Integer
    sample_size as Integer
    weights as List[Float]
    strata as List[List[Any]]
    replacement as Boolean

Type called "ReservoirSampler":
    reservoir as List[Any]
    reservoir_size as Integer
    items_seen as Integer
    generator as Generator.RandomGenerator

Type called "AliasTable":
    probabilities as List[Float]
    aliases as List[Integer]
    size as Integer
    generator as Generator.RandomGenerator

Type called "MCMCSampler":
    current_state as List[Float]
    target_distribution as Distribution
    proposal_distribution as Distribution
    generator as Generator.RandomGenerator
    burn_in as Integer
    thin as Integer
    samples_generated as Integer

Type Distribution is:
    | Custom with pdf as Process and support as List[Float]
    | Standard with dist as Distributions.Distribution

Note: Simple random sampling
Process called "sample" that takes population as List[Any] and k as Integer and generator as Generator.RandomGenerator returns List[Any]:
    Let n be Collections.List.length with lst as population
    If k is greater than n:
        Return Collections.List.copy with lst as population
    If k is less than or equal to 0:
        Return list
    Note: Use reservoir sampling for efficiency
    If k multiplied by 3 is less than n:
        Return sample_without_replacement with population as population and k as k and generator as generator
    Note: For large k relative to n, use shuffling
    Let indices be list
    For i from 0 to n - 1:
        Add i to indices
    shuffle with lst as indices and generator as generator
    Let result be list
    For i from 0 to k - 1:
        Add population at index (indices at index i) to result
    Return result

Process called "sample_without_replacement" that takes population as List[Any] and k as Integer and generator as Generator.RandomGenerator returns List[Any]:
    Let n be Collections.List.length with lst as population
    Let selected be Collections.Dict.create with pairs as list
    Let result be list
    For i from 0 to k - 1:
        Let j be Generator.next_int_range with generator as generator and min_val as 0 and max_val as (n - i - 1)
        While Collections.Dict.has_key with dict as selected and key as j:
            Set j to Collections.Dict.get with dict as selected and key as j
        Add population at index j to result
        Collections.Dict.set with dict as selected and key as j and value as (n - i - 1)
    Return result

Process called "sample_with_replacement" that takes population as List[Any] and k as Integer and generator as Generator.RandomGenerator returns List[Any]:
    Let n be Collections.List.length with lst as population
    Let result be list
    For i from 0 to k - 1:
        Let index be Generator.next_int_range with generator as generator and min_val as 0 and max_val as (n - 1)
        Add population at index index to result
    Return result

Note: Weighted sampling
Process called "weighted_sample" that takes population as List[Any] and weights as List[Float] and k as Integer and generator as Generator.RandomGenerator returns List[Any]:
    Let n be Collections.List.length with lst as population
    If Collections.List.length with lst as weights is not equal to n:
        Return list
    If k is greater than n:
        Return Collections.List.copy with lst as population
    Note: Create alias table for efficient sampling
    Let alias_table be create_alias_table with probabilities as weights and generator as generator
    Let result be list
    Let selected be Collections.Set.create()
    While Collections.List.length with lst as result is less than k:
        Let index be sample_from_alias_table with table as alias_table
        If not Collections.Set.contains with set as selected and element as index:
            Add population at index index to result
            Collections.Set.add with set as selected and element as index
    Return result

Process called "weighted_choice" that takes population as List[Any] and weights as List[Float] and generator as Generator.RandomGenerator returns Any:
    Let total_weight be 0.0
    For each weight in weights:
        Set total_weight to total_weight + weight
    Let r be Generator.next_double with generator as generator multiplied by total_weight
    Let cumulative be 0.0
    For i from 0 to Collections.List.length with lst as population - 1:
        Set cumulative to cumulative + (weights at index i)
        If r is less than or equal to cumulative:
            Return population at index i
    Return Collections.List.last with lst as population

Note: Reservoir sampling
Process called "create_reservoir_sampler" that takes k as Integer and generator as Generator.RandomGenerator returns ReservoirSampler:
    Return ReservoirSampler with:
        reservoir as list
        reservoir_size as k
        items_seen as 0
        generator as generator

Process called "reservoir_add" that takes sampler as ReservoirSampler and item as Any:
    Set sampler.items_seen to sampler.items_seen + 1
    If Collections.List.length with lst as sampler.reservoir is less than sampler.reservoir_size:
        Add item to sampler.reservoir
    Otherwise:
        Let j be Generator.next_int_range with generator as sampler.generator and min_val as 0 and max_val as (sampler.items_seen - 1)
        If j is less than sampler.reservoir_size:
            Set sampler.reservoir at index j to item

Process called "reservoir_sample" that takes sampler as ReservoirSampler returns List[Any]:
    Return Collections.List.copy with lst as sampler.reservoir

Note: Stratified sampling
Process called "stratified_sample" that takes strata as List[List[Any]] and proportions as List[Float] and total_size as Integer and generator as Generator.RandomGenerator returns List[Any]:
    Let result be list
    Let remaining be total_size
    For i from 0 to Collections.List.length with lst as strata - 1:
        Let stratum be strata at index i
        Let proportion be proportions at index i
        Let stratum_size be Integer.from with value as Math.round with x as (Float.from with value as total_size multiplied by proportion)
        If stratum_size is greater than remaining:
            Set stratum_size to remaining
        Let stratum_sample be sample with population as stratum and k as stratum_size and generator as generator
        Add all stratum_sample to result
        Set remaining to remaining - stratum_size
    Return result

Note: Latin hypercube sampling
Process called "latin_hypercube_sample" that takes n as Integer and dimensions as Integer and generator as Generator.RandomGenerator returns List[List[Float]]:
    Let samples be list
    For d from 0 to dimensions - 1:
        Let permutation be list
        For i from 0 to n - 1:
            Add i to permutation
        shuffle with lst as permutation and generator as generator
        Let dimension_samples be list
        For i from 0 to n - 1:
            Let interval_start be Float.from with value as (permutation at index i) divided by Float.from with value as n
            Let interval_end be Float.from with value as ((permutation at index i) + 1) divided by Float.from with value as n
            Let value be interval_start + Generator.next_double with generator as generator multiplied by (interval_end - interval_start)
            Add value to dimension_samples
        Add dimension_samples to samples
    Note: Transpose to get samples as rows
    Let result be list
    For i from 0 to n - 1:
        Let point be list
        For d from 0 to dimensions - 1:
            Add (samples at index d) at index i to point
        Add point to result
    Return result

Note: Alias method for discrete sampling
Process called "create_alias_table" that takes probabilities as List[Float] and generator as Generator.RandomGenerator returns AliasTable:
    Let n be Collections.List.length with lst as probabilities
    Let total be 0.0
    For each p in probabilities:
        Set total to total + p
    Let scaled_probs be list
    For each p in probabilities:
        Add (p divided by total) multiplied by Float.from with value as n to scaled_probs
    Let small be list
    Let large be list
    For i from 0 to n - 1:
        If scaled_probs at index i is less than 1.0:
            Add i to small
        Otherwise:
            Add i to large
    Let prob_table be Collections.List.copy with lst as scaled_probs
    Let alias_table be list
    For i from 0 to n - 1:
        Add i to alias_table
    While Collections.List.length with lst as small is greater than 0 and Collections.List.length with lst as large is greater than 0:
        Let l be Collections.List.pop with lst as small
        Let g be Collections.List.pop with lst as large
        Set alias_table at index l to g
        Set prob_table at index g to (prob_table at index g) + (prob_table at index l) - 1.0
        If prob_table at index g is less than 1.0:
            Add g to small
        Otherwise:
            Add g to large
    Return AliasTable with:
        probabilities as prob_table
        aliases as alias_table
        size as n
        generator as generator

Process called "sample_from_alias_table" that takes table as AliasTable returns Integer:
    Let i be Generator.next_int_range with generator as table.generator and min_val as 0 and max_val as (table.size - 1)
    Let p be Generator.next_double with generator as table.generator
    If p is less than (table.probabilities at index i):
        Return i
    Otherwise:
        Return table.aliases at index i

Note: Markov Chain Monte Carlo
Process called "create_mcmc_sampler" that takes initial_state as List[Float] and target as Distribution and proposal as Distribution and generator as Generator.RandomGenerator returns MCMCSampler:
    Return MCMCSampler with:
        current_state as initial_state
        target_distribution as target
        proposal_distribution as proposal
        generator as generator
        burn_in as 1000
        thin as 10
        samples_generated as 0

Process called "metropolis_hastings_step" that takes sampler as MCMCSampler:
    Let proposed be propose_state with sampler as sampler
    Let current_prob be evaluate_distribution with dist as sampler.target_distribution and state as sampler.current_state
    Let proposed_prob be evaluate_distribution with dist as sampler.target_distribution and state as proposed
    Let acceptance_ratio be proposed_prob divided by current_prob
    If acceptance_ratio is greater than or equal to 1.0:
        Set sampler.current_state to proposed
    Otherwise:
        Let u be Generator.next_double with generator as sampler.generator
        If u is less than acceptance_ratio:
            Set sampler.current_state to proposed
    Set sampler.samples_generated to sampler.samples_generated + 1

Process called "mcmc_sample" that takes sampler as MCMCSampler and n as Integer returns List[List[Float]]:
    Let samples be list
    Note: Burn-in period
    For i from 0 to sampler.burn_in - 1:
        metropolis_hastings_step with sampler as sampler
    Note: Sampling with thinning
    For i from 0 to n - 1:
        For j from 0 to sampler.thin - 1:
            metropolis_hastings_step with sampler as sampler
        Add Collections.List.copy with lst as sampler.current_state to samples
    Return samples

Process called "propose_state" that takes sampler as MCMCSampler returns List[Float]:
    Match sampler.proposal_distribution:
        When Standard with dist:
            Let proposal be list
            For each component in sampler.current_state:
                Let delta be Distributions.sample with sampler as Distributions.create_sampler with distribution as dist and generator as sampler.generator
                Add component + delta to proposal
            Return proposal
        When Custom:
            Return sampler.current_state

Process called "evaluate_distribution" that takes dist as Distribution and state as List[Float] returns Float:
    Match dist:
        When Standard with dist:
            Return 1.0 Note: Would evaluate actual PDF
        When Custom with pdf:
            Return 1.0 Note: Would call custom PDF

Note: Bootstrap and resampling
Process called "bootstrap_sample" that takes data as List[Any] and generator as Generator.RandomGenerator returns List[Any]:
    Let n be Collections.List.length with lst as data
    Return sample_with_replacement with population as data and k as n and generator as generator

Process called "bootstrap_statistic" that takes data as List[Float] and statistic as Process and n_bootstrap as Integer and generator as Generator.RandomGenerator returns List[Float]:
    Let results be list
    For i from 0 to n_bootstrap - 1:
        Let bootstrap_data be bootstrap_sample with data as data and generator as generator
        Let stat_value be calculate_statistic with data as bootstrap_data and statistic as statistic
        Add stat_value to results
    Return results

Process called "jackknife_samples" that takes data as List[Any] returns List[List[Any]]:
    Let n be Collections.List.length with lst as data
    Let samples be list
    For i from 0 to n - 1:
        Let sample be list
        For j from 0 to n - 1:
            If j is not equal to i:
                Add data at index j to sample
        Add sample to samples
    Return samples

Note: Permutation and combination utilities
Process called "shuffle" that takes lst as List[Any] and generator as Generator.RandomGenerator:
    Let n be Collections.List.length with lst as lst
    For i from n - 1 down to 1:
        Let j be Generator.next_int_range with generator as generator and min_val as 0 and max_val as i
        Let temp be lst at index i
        Set lst at index i to lst at index j
        Set lst at index j to temp

Process called "random_permutation" that takes n as Integer and generator as Generator.RandomGenerator returns List[Integer]:
    Let perm be list
    For i from 0 to n - 1:
        Add i to perm
    shuffle with lst as perm and generator as generator
    Return perm

Process called "random_combination" that takes population as List[Any] and r as Integer and generator as Generator.RandomGenerator returns List[Any]:
    Let n be Collections.List.length with lst as population
    If r is greater than n:
        Return list
    Let indices be sample_without_replacement with population as range_list with n as n and k as r and generator as generator
    Let result be list
    For each index in indices:
        Add population at index index to result
    Return result

Process called "random_subset" that takes population as List[Any] and generator as Generator.RandomGenerator returns List[Any]:
    Let n be Collections.List.length with lst as population
    Let size be Generator.next_int_range with generator as generator and min_val as 0 and max_val as n
    Return sample with population as population and k as size and generator as generator

Note: Importance sampling
Process called "importance_sample" that takes target_pdf as Process and proposal_pdf as Process and proposal_sampler as Process and n as Integer and generator as Generator.RandomGenerator returns List[Float]:
    Let samples be list
    Let weights be list
    For i from 0 to n - 1:
        Let x be call_process with process as proposal_sampler and args as list containing generator
        Let target_prob be call_process with process as target_pdf and args as list containing x
        Let proposal_prob be call_process with process as proposal_pdf and args as list containing x
        Let weight be target_prob divided by proposal_prob
        Add x to samples
        Add weight to weights
    Note: Normalize weights
    Let total_weight be 0.0
    For each w in weights:
        Set total_weight to total_weight + w
    For i from 0 to n - 1:
        Set weights at index i to (weights at index i) divided by total_weight
    Note: Resample according to weights
    Return weighted_sample with population as samples and weights as weights and k as n and generator as generator

Note: Rejection sampling
Process called "rejection_sample" that takes target_pdf as Process and proposal_sampler as Process and M as Float and generator as Generator.RandomGenerator returns Float:
    While true:
        Let x be call_process with process as proposal_sampler and args as list containing generator
        Let u be Generator.next_double with generator as generator
        Let target_prob be call_process with process as target_pdf and args as list containing x
        If u is less than or equal to (target_prob divided by M):
            Return x

Note: Systematic sampling
Process called "systematic_sample" that takes population as List[Any] and k as Integer and generator as Generator.RandomGenerator returns List[Any]:
    Let n be Collections.List.length with lst as population
    If k is greater than n:
        Return Collections.List.copy with lst as population
    Let interval be n divided by k
    Let start be Generator.next_int_range with generator as generator and min_val as 0 and max_val as (interval - 1)
    Let result be list
    For i from 0 to k - 1:
        Let index be start + (i multiplied by interval)
        If index is less than n:
            Add population at index index to result
    Return result

Note: Cluster sampling
Process called "cluster_sample" that takes clusters as List[List[Any]] and n_clusters as Integer and generator as Generator.RandomGenerator returns List[Any]:
    Let selected_clusters be sample with population as clusters and k as n_clusters and generator as generator
    Let result be list
    For each cluster in selected_clusters:
        Add all cluster to result
    Return result

Note: Utility functions
Process called "range_list" that takes n as Integer returns List[Integer]:
    Let result be list
    For i from 0 to n - 1:
        Add i to result
    Return result

Process called "calculate_statistic" that takes data as List[Float] and statistic as Process returns Float:
    Note: Would call the statistic function
    Let sum be 0.0
    For each value in data:
        Set sum to sum + value
    Return sum divided by Float.from with value as Collections.List.length with lst as data

Process called "call_process" that takes process as Process and args as List[Any] returns Any:
    Note: Would dynamically call the process with arguments
    Return 0.0